&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;J. B. Rainsberger&quot; &lt;jbrains@r...&gt;
&gt; wrote:
&gt;  &gt; claudioillanes wrote:
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Hi all,
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; I am new to JUnit and I&#39;ve trying to combine a sequence of
&gt;  &gt; &gt; testSuites. In one of my testXXX methods, I&#39;ve tried to create a
&gt;  &gt; &gt; TestSuite() (with a listing of  suite.addTest(new TestSuite
&gt;  &gt; &gt; (XXX.class)) ) and I want this testSuite to run its set of tests
&gt;  &gt; &gt; before this particular testXXX method completes. What I&#39;ve tried
&gt; is:
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; TestSuite packageSuite = new TestSuite();
&gt;  &gt; &gt; packageSuite.addTest( OtherFile.suite() );
&gt;  &gt; &gt; packageSuite.runTest(packageSuite, new TestResult());
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Is this right?
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; No.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; You appear to want to execute tests in a particular sequence; is
&gt; that
&gt;  &gt; correct? If so, simply add them in the desired sequence.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; public static Test suite() {
&gt;  &gt;      TestSuite packageSuite = new TestSuite();
&gt;  &gt;      packageSuite.addTest( OtherFile.suite() );
&gt;  &gt;      packageSuite.addTest( new MyTestCase(&quot;testMethod&quot;) );
&gt;  &gt;      ...
&gt;  &gt;      return packageSuite;
&gt;  &gt; }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; JUnit will do the rest.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Do not try to create suites at run time. Create the suite first,
&gt; then
&gt;  &gt; let JUnit run it.
&gt;  &gt; --
&gt;  &gt; J. B. Rainsberger,
&gt;  &gt; Diaspar Software Services
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Ok, I see. The thing is basically that according to a number I get in
&gt; one of the testXXX, I want to create an intermittent suite() that
&gt; runs a set of tests n times.  For example, I am running test A, and
&gt; in test A, I get a value 3 as the number of possible combinations to
&gt; test. 

What about this algorithm makes it a test? It sounds like it&#39;s just a 
&quot;suite builder&quot; method. If I am right, then that&#39;s all you need:

public static Test suite() {
     // determine how many tests to create
     // create the suite
}

It&#39;s not a test; it&#39;s just a suite builder. Does this method of yours 
/require/ a test being run to be invoked? Can you just invoke it outside 
the context of running a test?

 &gt; I then create a testSuite with a set of tests that will be run
&gt; referencing data according to their assigned indexes 0, 1, 2 .
&gt; (Representing three possible paths in the system to test). It may be
&gt; possible to find these values ahead of time, but that would result in
&gt; a tremendous increase in processing time, so I figured that if using
&gt; an intermittent suite() is a possibility, why not do it?

You could; but not the way you were trying to do it.

If your &quot;suite builder&quot; really is a test (and sometimes it is), then I 
think you have a serious design problem. Do something about it.

